{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"01790a33-2430-4486-8269-75ac81324b72","content":"Here's what you need:\n\n### 1. `Directory.Build.props` at the solution root\n\nCreate (or merge into) a shared props file so all three projects pick up the settings:\n\n```xml\n<Project>\n  <PropertyGroup>\n    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n\n  <ItemGroup>\n    <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" Version=\"1.5.3\" />\n  </ItemGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\n**What each property does:**\n- **`EnableMSTestRunner`** — switches from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner.\n- **`OutputType Exe`** — required because each test project now hosts its own process.\n- **`TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`** — lets `dotnet test` discover and run the new-platform executables (required on .NET 8 SDK; .NET 9+ enables this by default).\n\n### 2. Per-project changes\n\nNone, if the `Directory.Build.props` is at or above all three projects. Remove any per-project `<OutputType>Library</OutputType>` if explicitly set, since it would conflict.\n\n### 3. CI command\n\n```diff\n- dotnet test --logger trx\n+ dotnet test -- --report-trx\n```\n\n`--logger trx` is a VSTest argument. On Microsoft.Testing.Platform, TRX output comes from the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package and is enabled with `--report-trx`. The `--` separates `dotnet test` args from platform args.\n\nTRX files are written to each project's `TestResults/` folder, same as before.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"17aba45e-a5f1-430b-8559-1e087efaca27","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their MSTest 3.8.0 test projects from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a clear, concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration.\n\nKey changes needed:\n\n1. **Project-level**: Add `<EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>` and `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to each project, or better yet, use a `Directory.Build.props` to set it consistently.\n\n2. **MSTest 3.8.0 note**: With MSTest 3.8.0, the MSTest runner is already included via the `MSTest` meta-package or `MSTest.TestAdapter`. \n\n3. **Enabling the runner**: I need to make sure they actually enable it in their project files. The CLI commands will still use `dotnet test`, but the underlying execution changes when using Microsoft.Testing.Platform instead of VSTest.\n\nFor consistency across all projects, a `Directory.Build.props` file makes sense. The key property is `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` to ensure `dotnet test` integration works properly.\n\nFor TRX logging specifically, they'll need the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package and switch from `--logger trx` to `--report-trx` in their CI commands. Let me verify the exact syntax with .NET 8 SDK and MSTest 3.8.0. The native approach with the new testing platform uses `--report-trx` instead of the older `--logger trx` syntax. I need to set up a Directory.Build.props file with the testing platform configuration, add the TRX reporting package to the test projects, and update the CI command to use the new flag format.","outputTokens":1505,"requestId":"481E:99ACC:31C39E6:365026C:69FBE223"},"id":"ff03ef54-f470-4621-8eef-534338e3d57e","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:52:18.080Z","parentId":"dfd659bb-34c0-4b38-81ea-70360a80bb2b"}
